
@startuml

class Employee {
  - name: String
  - socialSecurityNumber: String
}

class CreativeEmployee {
  + isOscarWinner: Boolean
}

class Director {
  - assistantName: String
  * extends CreativeEmployee
}

class Actor {
  - education: String
  * extends CreativeEmployee
}

class Technician {
  - fieldOfActivity: String
}

Employee <|-- CreativeEmployee
CreativeEmployee <|-- Director
CreativeEmployee <|-- Actor
Employee <|-- Technician

class FilmSet {
  - location: String
  * has Films
}

class Film {
  - title: String
  - yearOfRelease: int
  - genre: String
  * has Employees
  * has Screenplay
  * has FilmSet
}

class Screenwriter {
  - name: String
  - mostSuccessfulFilm: String
  * creates Screenplay
}

class Screenplay {
  - title: String
  - version: String
  - date: Date
  - numberOfScenes: int
  - plot: String
  - basedOn: String (novel or concept)
  * has Novel
  * has Film
}

class Novel {
  - title: String
  - author: String
  * isBasedOn Screenplay
}

FilmSet "0..*" -- "1" Film: uses
Film "1" -- "0..*" Employee: has
Film "1" -- "1" Screenplay: basedOn
Screenplay "1" -- "1" Novel: basedOn
Screenwriter "1" -- "0..*" Screenplay: creates

@enduml

### Explanation of Relationships:
- `Employee` is the base class for all employees.
- `CreativeEmployee` is a subclass of `Employee`, and it includes `Director` and `Actor`.
- `Director` has an assistant name, and both `Director` and `Actor` can be Oscar winners.
- `Technician` has a field of activity.
- `FilmSet` is used by multiple `Film`s.
- `Film` has a title, release year, and genre. It also has a screenplay and may use one or more film sets.
- `Screenwriter` writes one or more `Screenplay`s.
- `Screenplay` is written for exactly one `Film` and can be based on a `Novel` or a concept.
- `Novel` is based on a `Screenplay`.

